        <h2 id="examples">Real product marketing examples</h2>
        <p>Three patterns from different business types:</p>

        <h3>1. Local accounting firm — service repositioning</h3>
        <p>A 12-person CPA firm launched CFO advisory services targeting existing tax clients. Product marketing approach: comparison documents positioning against hiring a full-time CFO (cost: £90,000+/year) versus fractional advisory (cost: £2,000/month), pilot client case studies showing specific financial outcomes, and email sequences to existing client list that led with the accountant's existing knowledge of their business. The positioning emphasised the firm's existing client relationship as the core differentiator — not the advisory service itself.</p>

        <h3>2. SaaS market expansion</h3>
        <p>A project management tool built for marketing agencies repositioned for construction companies. Product marketing work: website redesign with construction-specific language and case studies, competitive battle cards against Procore, and sales team briefing on construction industry workflows. Within 6 months, construction became the fastest-growing vertical — not because the product changed, but because the positioning and enablement did.</p>

        <h3>3. D2C brand repositioning</h3>
        <p>A skincare brand competing in a market with 200+ "clean beauty" competitors repositioned as "dermatologist-formulated ingredients." Product marketing output: new positioning statement, website copy overhaul, updated product descriptions emphasising specific ingredient percentages and clinical testing, and PR outreach to dermatology media. Result: 34% sales increase in 90 days with zero new product development.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Product marketing vs. content marketing — how they work together</h2>
        <p>These functions are complementary, not competing. The distinction in responsibilities matters for team structure and workflow.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Product marketing owns</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>What to say (positioning and messaging)</li>
              <li>Who to say it to (target buyer definition)</li>
              <li>Why it matters (value proposition)</li>
              <li>How it's different (competitive positioning)</li>
              <li>What evidence supports it (proof points)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Content marketing owns</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>How to say it (format, tone, format)</li>
              <li>Where to publish it (channel strategy)</li>
              <li>When to publish it (editorial calendar)</li>
              <li>How to make it rank (SEO optimisation)</li>
              <li>How to distribute it (promotion and amplification)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">8 best practices for effective product marketing</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Start with positioning before any other output.</strong> Battle cards, launch plans, and website copy all depend on the positioning being right. Teams that write collateral before defining positioning produce inconsistent messaging that gets corrected expensively later.</li>
          <li><strong>Interview lost deals, not just won ones.</strong> Win/loss analysis skewed toward won deals produces confirmation bias. Lost deal interviews reveal objections the team is not currently handling, competitor advantages the team has not addressed, and positioning gaps that position updates need to close.</li>
          <li><strong>Update battle cards every quarter.</strong> Competitors ship new features and change pricing continuously. A battle card built 12 months ago is likely outdated. Quarterly competitive review and battle card refresh is the minimum cadence for competitive markets.</li>
          <li><strong>Measure message adoption, not just asset creation.</strong> Producing a 20-slide sales deck is not product marketing success. Success is measured by whether sales reps are using it and whether it is influencing win rates. Track sales content usage and close rates for assets you create.</li>
          <li><strong>Brief sales before launch, not on launch day.</strong> Sales teams need 2+ weeks with new messaging before they pitch it to prospects. Briefings on launch day produce unprepared first calls that cost deals.</li>
          <li><strong>Align SEO content to product positioning.</strong> Blog posts and landing pages targeting competitor comparison keywords should reflect the same positioning hierarchy as sales collateral. Inconsistency between search content and sales messaging creates prospect confusion.</li>
          <li><strong>Use customer language, not internal language.</strong> Product teams describe features using internal technical terms. Customers describe problems using outcome terms. Product marketing translates between these — and the customer language always wins in external-facing assets.</li>
          <li><strong>Create a positioning statement before every launch.</strong> Even small feature launches benefit from a positioning statement that answers: who is it for, what problem does it solve, what is different about how we solve it, and what proof do we have? A two-paragraph positioning brief prevents 10 rounds of copy revision later.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — feature-led messaging</div>
          <p>Most product marketing produced without a dedicated PMM describes features, not outcomes. "We've added 200 new templates" is a feature announcement. "Agencies using our templates launch client campaigns 3x faster" is a product marketing message. The gap between these two approaches is directly measurable in conversion rates — feature-led messaging converts at significantly lower rates.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common product marketing mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Building collateral before positioning is agreed.</strong> If product, marketing, and sales disagree on the positioning, every asset produced from that undefined base needs to be rebuilt when the positioning is eventually defined.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping the competitive audit before a launch.</strong> Launching into a competitive market without understanding how each competitor is positioned means your launch messaging may inadvertently echo a competitor's — giving them credit for your differentiators.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating messaging frameworks as permanent.</strong> Positioning that was correct at Series A may be wrong at Series B. Markets evolve, competitors enter, and buyer maturity increases. Revisit positioning annually and after major product changes.</li>
          <li><strong>Producing sales enablement without involving sales.</strong> Battle cards built without input from the sales team often miss the objections reps actually encounter. Involve 3-4 reps in the drafting process before publishing final versions.</li>
          <li><strong>Measuring PMM output by volume.</strong> Number of assets created is an output metric. Win rate, pipeline influenced, and message adoption by sales are outcome metrics. Track outcomes, not outputs.</li>
        </ul>

